    "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    "code": "So if we send command = the one free direction, robot can't move (does nothing). If we send any other command, robot can choose the free direction (or others if they exist).\n\nSo for a cell with degree 1: send any command except the free direction \u2192 robot must go to that free neighbor (only valid option different from command). So we can FORCE the robot to move to its only free neighbor!\n\nFor a cell with degree 2: send command = one of the two free directions \u2192 robot must go to the other. We can choose which neighbor it goes to.\n\nFor a cell with degree \u2265 2: we can force the robot to go to any specific neighbor by commanding that direction. But the robot can choose among the other free neighbors.\n\nWait, with degree 2 neighbors A and B: command A \u2192 robot goes to B. Command B \u2192 robot goes to A. So we can force either direction!\n\nWith degree \u2265 3: command A \u2192 robot picks among B, C, ... We can't force a specific one.\n\nSo a cell is forceable if all its free neighbors are also forceable AND the degree \u2264 2? No wait...\n\nA cell is forceable if we can force the robot from it to the lab. This is a BFS/propagation problem.\n\nA cell `v` is forceable if:\n- It's the lab, OR\n- The number of free neighbors of `v` that are NOT yet known to be forceable is \u2264 1 (i.e., at most 1 non-forceable neighbor), meaning we can always command the non-forceable direction and force robot into forceable territory... \n\nActually: cell v is forceable if (number of free neighbors) - (number of forceable free neighbors) \u2264 1. Because we command one of the forceable neighbors, and the robot must pick from the remaining free neighbors. If all remaining (non-commanded) neighbors are forceable, we're good. But robot picks ONE of those.\n\nWait: if we command direction d (a forceable neighbor), robot picks any other free neighbor. If ALL other free neighbors are forceable, then wherever robot goes is forceable \u2192 eventually reaches lab. So:\n\n**v is forceable if (free_degree(v) - forceable_neighbors(v)) \u2264 1**\n\ni.e., at most 1 non-forceable neighbor. Because we command toward a forceable neighbor, and robot goes to one of the others - but if there's at most 1 non-forceable among the rest... no wait.\n\nIf non-forceable neighbors = 0: command any direction, robot goes to a forceable neighbor. \u2713\nIf non-forceable neighbors = 1: command the non-forceable one, robot goes to a forceable neighbor. \u2713  \nIf non-forceable neighbors \u2265 2: robot can always pick a non-forceable neighbor. \u2717\n\nSo: v is forceable iff (number of non-forceable free neighbors) \u2264 1.\n\nThis gives a BFS propagation: start with lab, propagate using the condition above.\n\nImplementation: maintain count of non-forceable neighbors for each cell. Initially all free cells have non_forceable_count = free_degree. When a cell becomes forceable, decrement neighbors' non_forceable counts, and if any drops to \u2264 1, that cell becomes forceable too.",
